Partially conditional survival models for liver related outcomes using HALT-C trial data

Marshall Brown and Yingye Zheng
16 October 2014

Data

HALT-C Trial Data:

We fit the model on non-treatment arm:

  • 533 individuals (134 observed outcomes)

We evaluate the model performance on the treatment arm:

  • 515 individuals (108 observed outcomes)

Outcomes of interest

We combine the following outcomes, using the first observed event time:

  1. Liver related death
  2. Hepatic Decompensation:
    • variceal bleed
    • ascites
    • bacterial perionitis
    • hepatic encephalopathy
  3. HCC or presumed HCC
  4. Liver transplant

Predictive markers of interest

Previous models (Ghany et. al)

Cox model using ALB, ASTALT, BIL, PLT baseline values and change in month 24 values to predict outcomes 2-4 (no death)

I replicated this model using our outcome, and extended it slightly:

  1. 'Discrete model' discretize marker values based on percent change
  2. 'Continous model' use continuous percent change as variable

PC Models (step 1 of 2)

For individual \( i \) and marker measurement \( j \) we smooth over marker values by modelling marker value \( Y \) with a mixed effects model:
\[ Y_{ij} = \beta_0 + \beta_1 *t + b_{0i} + b_{1i} *t + \epsilon \]

We wish to include the fitted \( \widehat{Y_{ij}} \) into a proportional hazards model to predict risk. However, \( \widehat{Y_{ij}} \) uses information across all measurement times, which we will not have when making predictions for new individuals. Thus, for a given time of prediction \( s_j \), we obtain the best linear unbiased predictor (blup) of \( \widehat{Y_{ij}} \) using measurement data only up to time \( s_j \).

PC Models (step 2 of 2)

Model 1 Use smoothed marker in a Cox model where \( \tau \) is the measurement time, and \( f \) is the natural cubic spline with two knots. Outcome time \( t \) is outcome time from measurement.

\[ \begin{aligned} \lambda(t|X) = \lambda_0(t|X)exp(f_1(\tau_i) &+ \beta_1 \widehat{PLT^{blup}_i} \\ & + \beta_2 \widehat{ALB^{blup}_i} \\ & + \beta_3 \widehat{APRI^{blup}_i} ) \end{aligned} \]

Model 2 Include random slope from the mixed effects models in the model as well.

Future Steps

  • Primary 'prediction' time 1 year in the future…maybe taylor partly conditional logistic model to focus on this aim.

  • We are primarily predicting HCC or Hepatic Decompinsation (because they often happen before liver transplant or death), we could build models to predict these outcomes separately.
